note.subjective: Client is a single parent of a child that is having reoccurent ear infections.  Client smokes in the home, with the child, but tries not to smoke near the child.  Client was able to quit smoking when pregnant with the child for the child's benefit.  Client has now started utilizing smoking as a relaxation technique.  Client is not sure about how successful they would be in stopping smoking at this time.  Client knows they should stop smoking, but also doubts their ability to stop smoking.
note.objective: Client would like to quit smoking.  Client is not sure of how successful she would be if attempting to stop smoking.
note.assessment: Client wants to quit smoking for the benefit to her child.  Client utilizes smoking as a relaxation technique.  Therapist discussed possible interventions to support client in smoking cessation including support groups and medications.  Client is open to support groups, if they have time or additional options.  Client does not like the idea of medication.
note.plan: Client will make another appointment with the therapist to discuss options to support in smoking cessation.

note.subjective: The client reports feeling stressed as a single mom with a full-time job, and uses smoking as a way to relax and destress. She is concerned about the impact of her smoking on her son's health, particularly with regards to his recent ear infections. She has tried to quit in the past, but has not been successful. She expresses a desire to quit, but is unsure of her ability to do so.
note.objective: The client appears anxious and uncertain about her ability to quit smoking. She is hesitant to commit to quitting, but is open to exploring options for support.
note.assessment: The client is struggling with nicotine addiction and is aware of the negative impact it has on her son's health. She has a history of quitting during pregnancy, but has not been able to sustain it. She is motivated to quit, but lacks confidence in her ability to do so.
note.plan: The client will return for a follow-up appointment to discuss options for quitting smoking, including support groups and classes. The therapist will explore ways to help the client build confidence in her ability to quit, and provide guidance on stress management techniques to replace smoking.

note.subjective: Client reports feeling stressed due to being a single mom with a full-time job. She has been smoking for 10 years, except during her pregnancy, and is aware of the potential health risks to her child, Aiden, who has had multiple ear infections. She expresses a desire to quit smoking but feels overwhelmed and unsure about her ability to do so. She rates her confidence in quitting as a 5 out of 10, acknowledging past success but current hesitation.
note.objective: Client appears stressed and overwhelmed. She is open to discussing her smoking habits and the impact on her child's health. She is receptive to the idea of seeking help to quit smoking but expresses concerns about time constraints and a dislike for medication.
note.assessment: Client is experiencing significant stress related to her responsibilities as a single parent and her job. Her smoking habit is a coping mechanism for stress, and she is aware of the potential health risks to her child. She has a history of successfully quitting smoking during pregnancy but currently feels ambivalent about her ability to quit again. Her motivation to quit is driven by concerns for her child's health and setting a good example.
note.plan: Short-term: Schedule a follow-up appointment to discuss smoking cessation options that fit into the client's lifestyle, such as support groups or classes. Long-term: Work on stress management techniques and explore alternative coping mechanisms to replace smoking. Aim to gradually increase the client's confidence in her ability to quit smoking and improve her overall well-being.

note.subjective: Client presented to therapy to discuss values. They completed a values clarification handout which was further reviewed with therapist. Client reports their top values are family happiness, inner harmony, health and security. They seemed to struggle with the differences in the value worksheet. Previously, religion was number one but now family happiness is number one. Client discussed how the first two values, especially family happiness takes up so much of their time and the other values take the back seat. Client talked about their family coming first and them having to take the back seat.  They stated "most of it goes to everything else, but me". Client talked about the struggles with inner harmony and lack of sleep. They report feeling overwhelmed. Their goal is to gain back inner harmony and peace.
note.objective: The client appears reflective and engaged in understanding their values. They regularly reassess their values every two to three months, indicating a proactive approach to personal growth. They articulate a clear understanding of the importance of family and religion in their life, despite current challenges. They also show awareness of their need for inner harmony and security but feel overwhelmed by their current focus on family issues, leading to neglect of their other values.
note.assessment: Client appears to be in the preparation stage of change. They are aware of the changes occurring in everyday life. Upon completing various sheets, client is aware of life changes, experiences and shifts in previous priorities. Client appears to have great insight into current life changes and how family has been the focal point lately. They appear highly motivated to work on developing balance among the different life areas and getting back to inner peace.
note.plan: Client will continue to explore values and changing family dynamics in next session.

note.subjective: The client reported feeling overwhelmed and struggling to prioritize their own needs, particularly inner harmony, health, and security. They expressed a strong desire to focus on family happiness and religion, but acknowledged that this has led to neglect of their own well-being. The client also mentioned feeling like they've lost sight of their faith and are struggling to reconcile their values with the challenges they're facing.
note.objective: The client appeared open and honest during the session, willing to explore their values and challenges. They demonstrated self-awareness and a desire to make positive changes in their life. However, they also seemed overwhelmed and uncertain about how to prioritize their own needs.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report, it appears that they are struggling to balance their own needs with their desire to prioritize family happiness and religion. This may be contributing to feelings of overwhelm and neglect of their own well-being. The client's values clarification exercise suggests that they are aware of the importance of inner harmony, health, and security, but are struggling to make these a priority.
note.plan: Short-term goals include helping the client identify ways to prioritize their own needs, particularly inner harmony, health, and security. This may involve exploring strategies for self-care, setting boundaries with family members, and finding ways to reconnect with their faith. Long-term goals include supporting the client in developing a more balanced approach to their values, and helping them to cultivate a greater sense of inner harmony and well-being.

note.subjective: The client reported that their top value is family happiness, which has become increasingly important due to recent family discord. They also mentioned that religion, previously their top value, has taken a backseat due to a loss of faith following a significant family situation. The client expressed a desire to be more present and understanding with their family members and to communicate the importance of family happiness to them. Additionally, the client identified health, inner harmony, and security as important values but noted that they have not been focusing on these as much due to the demands of family happiness and religion.
note.objective: The client appeared engaged and open during the session, discussing their values and the changes they have observed over time. They showed acceptance of their current state and a willingness to adapt to changes in their values. The client's mood was reflective and somewhat overwhelmed, with a focus on the importance of family happiness and a desire to regain inner harmony and peace.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report, it appears that they are experiencing a shift in their values, with family happiness taking precedence over religion due to recent family issues. The client is aware of the need to balance their values and is open to making changes to achieve inner harmony and better overall well-being. The client's acceptance of their current state and willingness to adapt suggests a positive outlook on personal growth and change.
note.plan: Short-term goals include exploring ways to communicate the importance of family happiness to family members and finding time for self-care to regain inner harmony. Long-term goals involve balancing all identified values (family happiness, religion, health, inner harmony, and security) and developing strategies to manage stress and overwhelm. The next session will focus on practical steps to achieve these goals, such as setting boundaries and prioritizing self-care activities.

note.subjective: Client is presenting to therapy and has expressed dissatisfaction with recent changes in the workplace. They report that their workplace has decided to go smoke-free. They state that they are not going to quit smoking as smoking helps them to relax. They report smoking a little less than a pack a day for the last five years. Client reports they are extremely confident that they could quit smoking if they wanted to, but they don't want to at the moment. However, upon therapist asking them, client reports they are a 2 on a scale of 1-10 in terms of readiness. Client reports if peers would quit smoking with them, it would make them feel more confident.
note.objective: Client appeared upset and annoyed during the beginning of the session. Initially, client reported they were confident about quitting smoking. However, client then admits they aren't as confident as the session proceeds.
note.assessment: Client appears to be in the pre-contemplation stage of change. When therapist asked on a scale of 1-10, client stated "I am probably a two." They do appear to be a little motivated but report they would be highly motivated if others would quit smoking as well.
note.plan: Client appeared receptive to therapist explaining the different products and information that could help curb the urge to smoke. They will follow up with therapist when they feel ready to explore products further.

note.subjective: The client is unhappy about their workplace going smoke-free and is not willing to quit smoking. They report smoking less than a pack a day for the last five years and feel confident that they could quit if they wanted to. They express a desire to find ways to cope with the new smoke-free policy at work.
note.objective: The client appears calm and relaxed during the session, with no observable signs of distress or anxiety. They maintain good eye contact and engage in conversation freely.
note.assessment: The client is currently not motivated to quit smoking, but is open to learning about options and tools that could help them in the future. They may be experiencing some resistance to the change in their workplace policy, but do not appear to be experiencing significant emotional distress.
note.plan: Short-term goals include providing the client with information about products and tools that can help with quitting smoking, and encouraging them to consider seeking support from friends or coworkers who may also be quitting. Long-term goals involve increasing the client's motivation to quit smoking and developing a quit plan. The next session will focus on exploring the client's values and goals related to smoking, and identifying potential barriers to quitting.

note.subjective: Client reports feeling unhappy about their workplace going smoke-free. They express a desire to continue smoking and mention that smoking helps them relax. Client smokes less than a pack a day and has been smoking for the last five years. They rate their readiness to quit smoking as a 2 on a scale of 1 to 10, indicating they have not seriously considered quitting but are open to the possibility. Client mentions that having a friend quit with them might help, but all their friends currently smoke.
note.objective: Client appeared calm and engaged during the session. They were able to articulate their feelings and thoughts about smoking and the workplace policy change. Client's mood was stable, and their affect was appropriate to the content of the conversation. Speech was clear and coherent.
note.assessment: Client is currently not ready to quit smoking but is open to the idea if certain conditions are met, such as having a friend quit with them. They are seeking information about quitting options and are aware of the workplace policy change. Client's attachment to smoking as a relaxation tool suggests a potential dependency, but they express confidence in their ability to quit if they choose to.
note.plan: Short-term: Provide client with information about nicotine replacement products and medications that can help with quitting. Encourage client to explore if any coworkers are planning to quit due to the workplace policy change. Long-term: Continue to support client's exploration of quitting smoking by discussing potential benefits and strategies. Monitor client's readiness to quit and provide resources as needed.

note.subjective: Client is presenting to therapy and would like to work adopting a healthier lifestyle. Client reports she would like to start working out again and having a healthy routine. Client reports she is tired of having low energy, being overweight and being unable to fit her current clothes. Client reports she feels uncomfortable with the way her clothes fit. Client's goal is to get back into an exercise routine, to feel healthy and be a good role model for her kids. Client discussed possible ways to go about exercising routine. At the same time, client is also trying to keep the balance and order of her current family routine.
note.objective: Client appears optimistic and internally motivated to make necessary changes to her lifestyle to improve her health.
note.assessment: Client appears to be in the preparation stage of change as evident through her ability to identify a plan of action regarding her workout routine.
note.plan: Client will identify which days she can exercise, walk, run and will work on developing a plan for those days.

note.subjective: Client reports feeling sluggish and uncomfortable with her current weight, wanting to start exercising again to feel healthy and be a good role model for her kids. She expresses motivation to change, citing past positive experiences with exercise and desire to feel good about herself.
note.objective: Client appears motivated and determined to make a change, but also expresses uncertainty about how to fit exercise into her schedule. She maintains good eye contact and engages in the conversation.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of feeling sluggish and uncomfortable with her weight, and her desire to be a good role model for her kids, it appears that she is struggling with low self-esteem and a lack of energy. She may be experiencing symptoms of depression, but further assessment is needed to determine the severity of her symptoms.
note.plan: Short-term goals include exploring options for exercise, such as finding a gym with daycare or scheduling walks/runs, and creating a routine that works with her family schedule. Long-term goals include improving overall physical health, increasing energy levels, and enhancing self-esteem. The next session will focus on developing a specific plan for incorporating exercise into her daily routine and addressing any obstacles that may arise.

note.subjective: Client expresses a desire to start working out again to feel healthier and have more energy, especially with the winter approaching. She feels sluggish and uncomfortable with how her clothes fit. She wants to be a good role model for her kids and knows that exercise has made her feel good in the past. She rates the importance of starting to exercise more as a 7 or 8 out of 10, indicating strong motivation but some logistical challenges.
note.objective: Client appears motivated and engaged in the conversation. She is able to articulate her reasons for wanting to exercise and the benefits she expects. She shows awareness of the need to balance her personal goals with family responsibilities.
note.assessment: Based on the client's self-report of feeling sluggish and uncomfortable with her current physical state, as well as her strong motivation to make a change, it appears she is experiencing a desire for lifestyle improvement. Her motivation is high, but she faces logistical challenges in scheduling exercise time around her family responsibilities.
note.plan: Short-term goals include helping the client identify specific times and methods for incorporating exercise into her routine, such as going for walks or runs and finding a nearby gym with daycare. Long-term goals involve maintaining a consistent exercise routine that balances her personal needs with her family responsibilities. Next session will focus on developing a concrete plan and addressing any barriers to implementation.

note.subjective: Client is speaking with therapist regarding previous behaviors which led to his phone privileges being taken away. He reports one of the officers has it out for him and took away his phone calls. Therapist spoke with client and talked about him being a model resident and getting released in three weeks. Client reports he just wants to be able to call his mom. Client usually contacts his mom every other day and hasn't been able to for the past week. Client reports he just wants to talk to his mom. In addition, he shared that tomorrow is his dad's birthday. Therapist feels client's behavior has more to do with anxiety over getting released soon versus phone call privileges.
note.objective: Client appears upset and annoyed over having phone calls revoked. He also appeared anxious over his upcoming release.
note.assessment: Client appears to be in the preparation stage of change.
note.plan: Client will potentially discuss his anxiety over getting released with therapist.

note.subjective: Client reports feeling frustrated and anxious about not being able to make a phone call to his mom, especially with his dad's birthday coming up tomorrow. He expresses feelings of being unfairly targeted by an officer and describes his current emotional state as difficult.
note.objective: Client appeared agitated and restless during the session, scoffing at the mention of the officer's actions. He maintained eye contact but had a tense posture.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of frustration and anxiety, as well as observable signs of agitation, it appears that the client may be experiencing increased stress and anxiety related to his upcoming release from the facility. The loss of phone privileges may be exacerbating these feelings, particularly given the significance of his dad's birthday.
note.plan: Short-term goals include working with the client to develop coping strategies for managing anxiety and frustration related to his phone privileges. We will also explore ways for the client to maintain contact with his mom, potentially through alternative means. Long-term goals involve preparing the client for his release by addressing underlying anxiety and stress related to re-entry into the community. Next session will focus on relaxation techniques and exploring the client's feelings about his upcoming release.

note.subjective: The client expressed frustration and anxiety over having their phone calls taken away. They mentioned feeling targeted by an officer for reasons they do not understand, such as not making their bed and their attitude. The client emphasized their desire to contact their mother and mentioned their father's birthday is tomorrow. They also acknowledged the upcoming release in three weeks.
note.objective: The client appeared agitated and frustrated during the session. They scoffed when discussing the officer's actions and repeatedly expressed their desire to make a phone call. The client's speech was coherent but showed signs of stress and anxiety.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of frustration and anxiety, as well as observable signs of agitation, the client may be experiencing increased stress and anxiety related to their upcoming release and the loss of contact with their mother. The client's behavior change could be a manifestation of these underlying stressors.
note.plan: Short-term goals include addressing the client's immediate frustration and anxiety by exploring coping mechanisms and possibly advocating for the restoration of phone privileges. Long-term goals involve preparing the client for their release by discussing strategies to manage anxiety and stress, and ensuring they have a support system in place, including regular contact with their mother.
